[{"location":"#Mathematical-pendulum-using-the-Runge-Kutta-method","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"This is the documentation for the repository of the homework 4 MathematicalpendulumusingtheRungeKuttamethod.jl of the Numerical Methods course. The documentation is divided into two parts. The first part provides a mathematical explanation of the pendulum and the Runge-Kutta method. The second part provides a technical explanation of the code we used to solve the given problem.","category":"page"},{"location":"#The-mathematical-explanation","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"The mathematical explanation","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"#Introduction","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Introduction","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"The point of the task is to develop a Numerical method for solving the mathematical pendulum problem. We have to construct a function 'nihalo' that will compute the displacement of the pendulum for a specific time. For this we will convert the second-order differential equation into a system of first-order equations and solve it using the fourth-order Runge-Kutta method.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"(Image: Equation)","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"At the end will also compered the whit a oscillating pendulum and a harmonic pendulum. ","category":"page"},{"location":"#Mathematical-pendulum-and-Harmonic-pendulum","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum and  Harmonic pendulum","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"The mathematical pendulum is a pendulum that is not affected by friction. On the image below, you can see the mathematical pendulum. Unlike the harmonic pendulum's sinusoidal motion, the oscillation period of a mathematical pendulum relies on initial conditions or energy.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"<p align=\"center\">   <img width=\"460\" height=\"300\" src=\"./images/Oscillating_pendulum.gif\"> </p>","category":"page"},{"location":"#Runge-Kutta-method","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Runge-Kutta method","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"The Runge-Kutta methods are a group of iterative methods used to solve ordinary differential equations (ODEs) and differential algebraic equations (DAEs).","category":"page"},{"location":"#The-code-explained-and-results","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"The code explained and results","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"First we initials the variables ","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"g = 9.80665 # gravitational acceleration for Earth\n\nl = 1 # length of the pendulum\nt = 10 # time\nn = 1000 # number of time steps\ntheta0 = deg2rad(30) # initial angle\ndtheta0 = deg2rad(1) # initial angular velocity","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"Then we define the function 'nihalo' that will compute the displacement of the pendulum for a specific time. For this we will convert the second-order differential equation into a system of first-order equations and solve it using the fourth-order Runge-Kutta method.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"function nihalo(l, t, theta0, dtheta0, n,g)\n    h = t / n  # step size\n\n    y = [theta0, dtheta0]  # initial conditions\n    theta_vals = [theta0]  # store the solution here\n\n    for _ in 1:n-1  # loop over time steps\n        k1 = h .* derivatives(y, l, g)\n        k2 = h .* derivatives(y + 0.5 .* k1, l, g)\n        k3 = h .* derivatives(y + 0.5 .* k2, l, g )\n        k4 = h .* derivatives(y + k3, l,g)\n        y += (k1 + 2 .* k2 + 2 .* k3 + k4) / 6.0\n        push!(theta_vals, y[1])\n    end \n    \n    return theta_vals\n\nend","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"The we plot the results for the mathematical pendulum","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"plot(t_vals, theta_vals, label=\"Mathematical pendulum\", xlabel=\"Time [s]\", ylabel=\"Displacement [rad]\")","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"the resulting graf is: ","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"<img title=\"Displacement of a Pendulum over Time\" alt=\"Alt text\" src=\".\\images\\Displacement of a Pendulum over Time.JPG\">","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"Then we define the function 'harmonic' that will compute the displacement of the harmonic pendulum for a specific time.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"function harmonic_oscillator(l, t, theta0, dtheta0,g)\n    return theta0 * cos(sqrt(g/l) * t) + dtheta0/sqrt(g/l) * sin(sqrt(g/l) * t)\nend","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"The we plot the results for the harmonic pendulum","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"plot(t_vals, harmonic_oscillator.(l, t_vals, theta0, dtheta0,g), label=\"Harmonic oscillator\", xlabel=\"Time [s]\", ylabel=\"Displacement [rad]\")","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"the resulting graf is:   <img title=\"Displacement of a Harmonic Oscillator over Time\" alt=\"Alt text\" src=\".\\images\\Displacement of a Harmonic Oscillator over Time.JPG\">","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"Then we define the function 'period' that will compute the period of the pendulum for a specific energy.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"function period(l, t, theta0, dtheta0, n,g)\n    theta = nihalo(l, t, theta0, dtheta0, n, g)\n    h = t / n  # time step\n    t_half_period = argmin(abs.(theta .- theta0)) * h\n    return 2 * t_half_period\nend\n\nfunction find_period(displacement, h)\n    peaks = findall(diff(sign.(diff(displacement))) .< 0)\n    return peaks[2] * h - peaks[1] * h\nend\n\nfunction energy(l, theta, dtheta,g)\n    return 0.5 * l^2 * dtheta^2 + g * l * (1 - cos(theta))\nend","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"The we plot the results for the period of the pendulum as a function of energy","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"plot(energy.(l, theta_vals, dtheta_vals,g), period.(l, t, theta_vals, dtheta_vals, n,g), label=\"Period of a Pendulum as a Function of Energy\", xlabel=\"Energy [J]\", ylabel=\"Period [s]\")","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"the resulting graf is:","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"<img title=\"Period of a Pendulum as a Function of Energy\" alt=\"Al t text\" src=\".\\images\\Period of a Pendulum as a Function of Energy.JPG\">","category":"page"},{"location":"#Conclusion","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Conclusion","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"I think the method I used is good for solving the mathematical pendulum problem. The results are similar to the results of the harmonic pendulum.  As for the the energy of the pendulum, the results are as expected I think. The higher the energy, the longer the period of the pendulum.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","title":"Mathematical pendulum using the Runge Kutta method","text":"docs\\src","category":"page"}]
